
[1]bernardins

   BER'NARDINS, n. An order of monks, founded by Robert, abbot of Moleme,
   and reformed by St. Bernard. The order originated about the beginning
   of the 12th century. They wear a white robe, with a black scapulary;
   and when they officiate, they are clothed with a large white gown, with
   great sleeves, and a hood of the same color.
